Def — the method form.

The everyday way to declare a piece of executable code in Scala is def. It defines a method, which is a member of a class, a trait, or a singleton object. A top-level def, with no enclosing object, compiles to a static method behind the scenes.

The full shape, with the optional parts included, is the keyword def, then a method name, then an optional type-parameter list in square brackets, then a parameter list in parentheses, then a colon and a return type, then an equals sign, then the body. Picture a small square method that takes an integer and returns x times x, or a method that computes the hypotenuse from two sides — same skeleton each time.

Two things to remember from the start.

First, the return type can be inferred, but for public methods you should write it. The rule from notebook two applies here even more strongly — the return type is part of the method's contract with its callers.

Second, the last expression in the body is the return value. There is no return keyword needed. You can write return, but in idiomatic Scala you almost never see it — it is mostly a debugging escape hatch. The value of the method is simply the value of its final expression.
